f.next = next\nclass Solution:\n    def deleteMiddle(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\n# Definition for singly-linked list.\n# class ListNode:\n#     def __init__(self, val=0, next=None):\n#         self.val = val\n#         self.next = next\nclass Solution:\n    def deleteMiddle(self, head: Optional[ListNode]) -> Optional[ListNode]:\n        if not head or not head.next:\n            return None\n        \n        slow = head\n        fast = head\n        prev = None\n        \n        while fast and fast.next:\n            prev = slow\n            slow = slow.next\n            fast = fast.next.next\n        \n        if prev:\n            prev.next = slow.next\n        \n        return head\n```\n\nThis solution uses the two-pointer technique (slow and fast pointers) to find the middle node of the linked list. The `prev` pointer is used to keep track of the node before the slow pointer so that we can easily remove the middle node by adjusting the `next` pointer of the `prev` node. If the list has only one node, it returns `None` as there is no node left after deletion.", "estimated_date": 1638662400000}